{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox military person |name= Nur Mohammad Sheikh |native_name=নূর মোহাম্মদ শেখ |native_name_lang=ben |birth_date={{birth-date|26 February 1936}} |death_date={{death-date and age|5 September 1971|26 February 1936}} |birth_place= Moheshkhali, [[Narail]] |death_place= Goalhati, [[Jessore]] |image=Nur mohammad thumb.jpg |image_size= |caption=[[Lance Nayek]] , Nur Mohammad Sheikh [[Bir Sreshtho]] |nickname= |allegiance= [[Bangladesh]] |serviceyears= |rank= [[Lance Nayek]] |commands= |unit= [[East Pakistan Rifles]] |battles=[[Bangladesh Liberation War]] |awards= [[Bir Sreshtho]] |laterwork= }} '''Nur Mohammad Sheikh''' ({{lang-bn|নূর মোহাম্মদ শেখ}}; 26 February 1936 – 5 September 1971) was a [[Lance Nayek]] in [[East Pakistan Rifles]] during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War|Liberation War]]. He was killed in an engagement with the Pakistan Army while providing fire for covering the extrication of fellow soldiers at Goalhati in Jessore district on 5 September 1971. Nur Mohammad died saving his compatriots and inflicting heavy casualties on his enemy. He was awarded [[Bir Sreshtho]], the highest state insignia of Bangladesh for his bravery and the highest sacrifice.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Unb|title=FFs are greatest sons of soil: President|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/cache/cached-news-details-64422.html|website=thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>
{{Campaignbox Bangladesh Liberation War}}
==Early life== Nur Mohammad Sheikh was born in February 26, 1936, in Moheshkhali village [[Narail]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mukul|first1=Manzurul Alam|title=Bir Shrestha Nur Mohammad`s death anniversary today|url=http://www.risingbd.com/english/Bir_Shrestha_Nur_Mohammads_death_anniversary_today/17557|website=risingbd.com|publisher=risingbd.com|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> His father is Mohammad Amanat Sheikh and his mother's name Mosammat Jinnatunnesa Khanam. He lost his parents at an early age and continued his education up to seventh grade at local schools. Early as a child he loved theatre.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|last1=Amin|first1=Tusher|title=The battle of Goalhati|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=248380|website=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>
On 14 March 1959, he joined the [[East Pakistan Rifles]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=Bir Shrestha Nur Mohammad's death anniv today|url=http://www.newstoday.com.bd/?option=details&news_id=2388501&date=2014-09-05|website=newstoday.com.bd|publisher=the Editor on behalf of Newscorp Publications Limited|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> After finishing elementary training, he was appointed at the [[Dinajpur District, Bangladesh|Dinajpur]] sector.<ref name="auto"/> He was transferred to [[Jessore]] sector on 1 July 1970. In March 1971, Nur Mohammad was spending a vacation at his village. As the war started, he joined sector 8 and continued to take part at different battles at Jessore. He died on 5 September during the Goalhati Battle in Sutipur.
==Battle of Goalhati and Death== Lance Nayek Nur Mohammad was selected as the captain of the Standing Patrol team at Goalhati in Jessore's Ghutipur Camp that was established to monitor the Pakistan army.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Editor|title=Sheikh, Birsrestha Nur Mohammad|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Sheikh,_Birsrestha_Nur_Mohammad|website=en.banglapedia.org|publisher=Banglapedia|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> On 5 September, Nur Mohammad was patrolling with 4 fellow soldiers. The Pakistan army managed to point out the position of Nur Mohammad's team and attacked them from three different sides. Nur Mohammad wanted to retreat to his base and continued to fire towards Pakistani armies. Meanwhile, one of his fellow soldiers, Nannu Mia, was shot by a bullet and Nur Mohammad started carrying him towards safety. But Nur Mohammad himself was hit by a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] and his foot was destroyed. Even though he was seriously injured, Nur Mohammad decided to continue to provide covering fire for his team. At the time, his fellow Sepoy, Mostafa, urged Nur Mohammad to go with him. Mostafa even tried to force Nur Mohammad to go but Nur Mohammad refused to go but gave his Light Machine Gun to Mostafa so that it would not be captured after his death. He kept a self loaded rifle with him and kept on fighting until he died.<ref name="auto"/>
==Legacy== Birshreshtha Noor Mohammad Public College at [[Pilkhana, Bangladesh|Pilkhana]] has been named in his memory.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Admin|title=Welcome|url=http://www.noormohammadcollege.ac.bd/Home.aspx|website=noormohammadcollege.ac.bd|publisher=Birshreshtha Noor Mohammad Public College|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> He is survived by his widow Begum Fazilatunnesa and son Golam Mostafa.<ref>{{cite web|last1=BSS|title=Bir Shrestha Nur Muhammad's death anniv observed|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/old/index.php?ref=MjBfMDlfMDdfMTNfMV84OF8xODI1Nzg=|website=thefinancialexpress-bd.com|publisher=the Editor for International Publications Limited|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> He was buried in Kashipur under Sharsha upazila of Jessore district.<ref>{{cite web|last1=BSS|title=43rd death anniversary of Bir Shrestha Nur Mohammad tomorrow|url=http://www.bssnews.net/newsDetails.php?cat=4&id=434300&date=2014-09-04|website=bssnews.net|publisher=bssnews.net|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref> A hospital in Jessore is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Admin Info|title=ABOUT US|url=http://jhenaidahcadetcollege.jessoreboard.gov.bd/2100/history-of-institution.html|website=jhenaidahcadetcollege.jessoreboard.gov.bd|publisher=JHENAIDAH CADET COLLEGE|accessdate=19 June 2015}}</ref>
